Class SessionStatusListenerBase

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.util.configuration.AbstractConfigurable
      • com.camerontec.catalys.server.component.ComponentHelper
        • com.camerontec.catalys.server.sessionmanager.SessionStatusListenerBase
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ISessionStatusEventListener, ISessionStatusListener, IComponent, ISessionManagerListener, IHasAttributes, IConfigurable, IRegisterable, ICatalysEventListener, EventListener
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SampleMonitor

    public abstract class SessionStatusListenerBase
extends ComponentHelper
implements ISessionStatusListener, ISessionManagerListener
    Base implementation of ISessionStatusListener. It is also an ISessionManagerListener which means that it can be registered as a Session listener directly by calling a Session's addSessionStatusEventListener or a SessionManager's ISessionManager.addListener(ISessionManagerListener) addListener}.

    Typically your own listeners will subclass this, overriding those methods where you want non-null processing.

      • onInMessageDecrypted

        public void onInMessageDecrypted(CatalysEventObject event,
                                 IFIXMessage message)
        Does nothing.

        NOTE:
        This should NOT be used to retrieve a message for processing. It is intended to simply signal that a message has arrived. Messages should be retrieved using the Session's getMessage method. This will ensure that messages are processed in the correct order and are correctly removed from the internal application queue.

      • shouldReceiveHighVolumeEvents

        public boolean shouldReceiveHighVolumeEvents()
        Description copied from interface: ISessionStatusEventListener
        Some session events occur at high volume, i.e. per message. If this method returns false, then the Session can possibly avoid notifications for these events which improves performance.
        Specified by:
        shouldReceiveHighVolumeEvents in interface ISessionStatusEventListener
        Returns:
        whether high volume events should be delivered
